  "number": "3.2",
  "title": "Semiregular Polyhedra",
  "body": " Semiregular Polyhedra   Defining Semiregular Polyhedra  We now extend our collection of polyhedra by exploring what it means for a polyhedron to be semiregular and to construct some examples.   semiregular polyhedron  polyhedron semiregular  vertex arrangement polyhedron   A polyhedron is semiregular if it satisfies the following conditions:  Every face is a regular polygon.  At least two polygonal faces have a different number of sides.  The arrangement of polygons at every vertex of the polyhedron are the same.    The notation for a vertex arrangement of a polyhedron is the same as what we used for tilings. A cube would be denoted 4.4.4 because there are three squares meeting at any vertex of the cube.    Check your Understanding  Which regular polyhedron corresponds to the notation 3.3.3.3.3?   Does the number 3 correspond to the shape of the face or the number of faces that meet?    The icosahedron because five triangles meet at each vertex.     Some Examples of Semiregular Polyhedra     One example of a semi-regular polyhedron is the great rhombicosi dodecahedron pictured. Check that each vertex has the arrangement 4.6.10. What is the sum of the angles meeting at each vertex of the great rhombicosi dodecahedron?   Great Rhombicosidodecahedron   The front side of a great rhombicosidodecahedron. Five decagonal faces, eight hexagonal faces, and eight square faces are clearly visible, but there is a hint of a square and hexagon alonge the bottom edge.            "
