  "title": "Compositions of Reflections",
  "body": " Compositions of Reflections   Compositions  Each of the transformations we have studied so far, reflections, translations, and rotations, perform an action on the points of the plane. In fact, a transformation is a function where the inputs are geometric objects instead of numbers. In algebra, you learned about the add three function, , and the multiply by four function, . You also learned that you could perform two functions in succession. For example, you could perform the add three function on the number and then perform the multiply by 4 function on the result. In function notation, we may write where we perform the inner function first. We may also perform these operations on a generic value : We note the importance of order. If we multiply by 4 first and add 3 second, we get a different result:   We now explore what happens when we compose geometric transformations. We could compose any two transformations, but we will first focus on reflections. What happens when we perform two or more reflections in succession? Do we get another reflection? Does it matter whether the lines are parallel? Does the order in which we perform the reflections matter?   composition  A composition of two transformations is a sequence of two transformations, and , performed in succession. To find the image of a point under the composition, followed by , written , one first finds the image of under the action of and then finds the image of under .     Reflecting across Parallel Lines    An interactive Geogebra applet for reflecting across parallel lines.    First explore what happens when you reflect an object first over line and then over line where and are parallel.  Use the reflect across line tool that looks like a red and blue dot on opposite sides of a diagonal line. Select the tool, select the pentomino, and then select the line. When you reflect across the second line be sure to reflect the new pentomino , not the original. Geogebra should label the vertices of the final object with , etc. You may choose to hide (use show\/hide tool) the intermediate objects or color the initial and final objects (use right-click on the interior of the pentomino) so that it is easier to focus on the first and final figures.   What type of isometry takes to ? Is it a reflection, a translation, a rotation, or something else?    Refer to or the table you created at the end of . What is the defining object for the isometry taking to ? Use the appropriate tools to locate and sketch the defining object for this isometry.    Add  add  Add  Reflecting across intersecting lines  Add  Is the composition of two isometries always an isometry? What type? The chart will be useful in answering these questions! Fill it out to the best of your ability now even if you’re not 100% certain of your answers. You will have a chance to revise and add to this chart later.   "
